# Sleep Quality Monitor — Project Proposal

## What data will be collected and why

This project tracks bedroom environmental conditions overnight  specifically temperature, humidity, noise level, and light exposure  and uses that data to generate a nightly sleep quality score. These are the factors that most directly affect how well you sleep, but almost no one actually measures them.

The sensor will sample every 30 seconds throughout the night and send each reading to a cloud backend. Over time, the dashboard builds up a history so you can see patterns across days and weeks.

## Hardware

The sensor unit is built around an ESP32, which is essentially an Arduino with built-in WiFi. Since the project requires sending data over the network, this is the right choice over a plain Arduino. Attached to it are a DHT22 for temperature and humidity, a small sound sensor module for detecting noise, and a photoresistor for measuring light levels. Total cost is around $22. The device sits on a nightstand and runs off a USB cable overnight.

## What the end user sees

The dashboard has two main views. The first is a nightly summary a timeline of temperature, noise, and light across the night, an estimated lights-out and wake time based on the light sensor, and a sleep quality score from 0 to 100 calculated from how well the room conditions held up through the night. The second is a weekly trends view showing how scores have changed day to day along with averages for temperature and noise.

## Basic goals

- ESP32 reads all sensors and posts data every 30 seconds
- FastAPI backend receives readings and stores them in PostgreSQL
- All API requests are token-protected
- Dashboard shows last night's chart and sleep score
- Deployed to the cloud via Docker

## Stretch goals

- Multi-user accounts with login
- Weekly summary email with personalized recommendations
- Real-time chart updates during the night
